WEBVTT

00:12.866 --> 00:16.712
Again, Colossians chapter four, beginning at verse two.

00:18.495 --> 00:24.444
Continue earnestly in prayer, being diligent, vigilant in it with thanksgiving.

00:24.504 --> 00:38.866
Meanwhile, praying also for us that God would open to us a door for the word to speak the mystery of Christ for which I am also in chains.

00:40.450 --> 00:43.794
that I may make it manifest as I ought to speak.

00:45.196 --> 00:49.681
Walking wisdom toward those who are outside, redeeming the time.

00:49.721 --> 01:02.357
Let your speech always be with grace, seasoned with salt, that you may know how you ought to answer each one.

01:03.538 --> 01:06.802
This is the Word of God for the people of God.

01:07.554 --> 01:07.994
Amen.

01:08.014 --> 01:10.737
May God add his blessing to the reading of this word you may be seeing.

01:16.944 --> 01:21.008
We're going to grab some verses in the scriptures in a couple of different places.

01:21.028 --> 01:26.494
So if you like to follow along or take notes you can write them and I'll share with you what those are as we get to them.

01:28.937 --> 01:34.162
Today we're talking about something that is dear to my heart and

01:35.906 --> 01:46.818
I really think that when we talk about a church and life of a church, one of the most important things to talk about is how people feel when they walk in the door for the first time.

01:50.182 --> 02:02.536
When you walk into somebody's home or a business or anything that you've never been to and you feel like you're really welcome, you feel it before anybody says a word on many occasions.

02:02.776 --> 02:04.178
You just know you're welcome.

02:04.258 --> 02:12.611
There may be eye contact or laughter, people enjoying one another, and a sense that someone's glad you're there, or they want you there.

02:13.532 --> 02:14.274
And that's true.

02:14.834 --> 02:19.662
In a business, it's true for a home, it's true for relationships, it's also true for a church.

02:21.845 --> 02:29.938
And what's interesting and what I don't like this statistic, as a matter of fact, I wish it was a vice versa.

02:31.266 --> 02:35.330
But visitors rarely remember the sermon first.

02:37.913 --> 02:43.419
They remember the atmosphere and the mood of the service and the people.

02:43.819 --> 02:44.940
That's what they comment on.

02:44.960 --> 02:49.385
They don't go, yeah, it was a great sermon and it had a people okay too.

02:50.026 --> 02:52.328
They go, it's great people and the sermon wasn't bad.

02:52.788 --> 02:58.194
If you've got a church that's warm and inviting and the sermon's only okay, people are okay with that.

02:58.722 --> 03:02.206
You got a great sermon and the church is cold and unfriendly.

03:02.427 --> 03:03.888
They're not so happy about that.

03:04.069 --> 03:06.812
And they're less likely to return because of that.

03:08.314 --> 03:10.136
But they remember that atmosphere.

03:10.176 --> 03:18.326
So before they meet the pastor, they meet the spirit, if you will, of the house of God, what it's like to be there.

03:20.629 --> 03:24.093
I think we are a very welcoming church.

03:27.537 --> 03:28.178
Are you?

03:28.514 --> 03:34.761
A part of that, are you a welcoming person seeking out people who come to make sure they've been seen?

03:36.844 --> 03:37.685
It's important for me.

03:39.127 --> 03:43.932
Maybe you know this about me to try to remember to shake everybody's hand and greet everybody.

03:43.992 --> 03:48.418
This might be the only time this week that I get a chance to do that.

03:49.799 --> 03:52.082
And I don't know when the next time will be.

03:53.090 --> 03:56.695
And it's not something where I go, I need to do this out of obligation.

03:56.715 --> 03:59.980
I do it because I like to meet people and see how they're doing.

04:00.040 --> 04:05.308
I don't want to miss that opportunity to say hello and see if anybody needs to say anything.

04:06.670 --> 04:12.479
It also fulfills a scripture that I didn't intentionally fill by doing it.

04:13.580 --> 04:14.642
And when we do that,

04:15.714 --> 04:45.106
when it matters to us that scriptures feel filled even better it's a Romans 15 seven it says therefore receive one another just as Christ also received us to the glory of God so we receive one another when we welcome each other the message today called the doors and arms it's one of those titles that

04:45.218 --> 04:55.635
needs an explanation because you open a door, you want to know when someone opens the door to you what the heart is behind the welcome that you get.

04:56.997 --> 05:00.703
In the New Testament times, hospitality was very critical.

05:00.983 --> 05:02.967
That's why Jesus turned the water into wine.

05:03.307 --> 05:12.562
That's why he helped so many people who asked for it because he didn't turn people down and having a successful wedding at the Cana

05:13.026 --> 05:18.356
was something that would have brought shame if it was not, so he helped out.

05:19.077 --> 05:26.030
And it still brings true about hospitality in the Middle Eastern lands today in certain areas.

05:26.531 --> 05:36.690
And when I learned what that meant and learning what that means to them by hospitality changes how you read the Bible.

05:38.722 --> 05:47.290
I had an opportunity to go to a lecture one time from a man who was raised there, but was pastoring the United Methodist Church out of California.

05:47.331 --> 06:03.246
And he told a story about his son asking him one day, and they were teenagers, the son and his friend, ask him if his son, if his friend of his son could come to dinner.

06:04.247 --> 06:07.090
He said, Dad can, I don't remember what he said,

06:07.170 --> 06:11.696
son's friend's name was, but he said, do you know what you're asking?

06:12.837 --> 06:13.738
He said, I think so.

06:14.058 --> 06:22.769
And he said, son, in our culture, if someone sits at our table, we become responsible for them like their family, no matter who it is.

06:25.132 --> 06:25.893
He's okay, dad.

06:26.353 --> 06:27.555
Oh, so is that a yes?

06:28.496 --> 06:30.438
Didn't really pay much attention, right?

06:32.040 --> 06:36.626
So his dad let his friend come and eat, they ate, and

06:36.706 --> 06:37.727
He didn't think anything of it.

06:40.249 --> 06:44.694
A few weeks later, the son and his friend got into some trouble.

06:46.115 --> 06:51.180
The kind of trouble ends you up in jail for a little while, as teenager.

06:51.880 --> 06:53.122
He calls his dad.

06:54.743 --> 06:55.344
This is dad.

06:56.545 --> 06:58.967
My friend and I were out doing some stupid stuff.

06:59.027 --> 06:59.848
I got in trouble.

06:59.868 --> 07:01.289
Can you come bail me out?

07:02.531 --> 07:04.813
Dad says, you're my son.

07:04.873 --> 07:06.034
I'm responsible.

07:06.274 --> 07:10.400
for what goes on in your life until you're not my son and you're out of the house.

07:10.981 --> 07:12.263
Yes, I will come.

07:13.565 --> 07:17.091
Well, the son told his friend dad's coming.

07:18.113 --> 07:21.097
The other boy said, my dad can't afford it.

07:22.139 --> 07:24.342
And I can't call him.

07:24.362 --> 07:25.224
I don't have any call.

07:25.725 --> 07:28.088
And he said, well, I'll see what I can do when I get out.

07:29.491 --> 07:34.258
Well, as soon as the bailiff, I guess it's the bailiff that comes and get him out of the jail.

07:34.594 --> 07:45.144
or the sheriff, I don't even know because I've never had that experience, but they came to get his son out of jail and he said, and you too.

07:47.386 --> 07:48.807
You saw, oh, someone bailed him out?

07:49.368 --> 07:51.490
And I said, yes, he's been bailed out too.

07:52.151 --> 07:54.072
And the bail was thousands of dollars.

07:55.334 --> 08:03.241
When they walked out, it was just his dad there and he said, Dad, who bailed him out?

08:03.261 --> 08:04.242
He said, I did.

08:04.354 --> 08:05.275
He said, why?

08:05.656 --> 08:07.739
He ate at my table.

08:08.360 --> 08:11.705
I treat him just the same as I treat you.

08:14.089 --> 08:14.950
We don't think like that.

08:15.891 --> 08:16.753
That's not how we do it.

08:17.013 --> 08:18.395
But that's how they do it.

08:18.776 --> 08:25.886
It's a very important thing if someone sits at your table in that culture that you are responsible for them like they're your own.

08:26.868 --> 08:28.250
And so that's what his son learned.

08:28.270 --> 08:28.951
That's what he taught us.

08:28.971 --> 08:31.154
So when you see that in the Bible playing out,

08:31.234 --> 08:43.346
or people who are at meals, you'll see that the host is responsible to that people that came for the rest of their immature ages until they grow to have their own home.

08:48.911 --> 09:00.402
In Acts chapter 2, verses 42 through 47, it talked about the church growing, but the church didn't grow

09:00.674 --> 09:07.783
through events, activities, going to do things, it grew through the embrace of people.

09:13.410 --> 09:22.322
In Acts chapter 2 you may remember when the Holy Spirit was poured out and in verses 42 through 47 this is what happened.

09:24.482 --> 09:35.013
They continued steadfastly in the apostles' doctrine and fellowship in the breaking of bread and in prayers, and fear came on every soul, and many wonders and signs were done through the apostles.

09:35.553 --> 09:39.177
All who believed were together and had all things in common.

09:39.197 --> 09:42.861
They sold their possessions and goods, divided them among all as anyone had need.

09:43.381 --> 09:52.210
So continuing daily with one another in the temple, and breaking bread from house to house, they ate their food with gladness and simplicity of heart.

09:53.314 --> 10:03.187
Praising God and having favor with all the people and the Lord added to the church daily those were being saved They went from home to home breaking bread sharing the good news.

10:03.808 --> 10:06.912
That's how the church grew They didn't say come to us.

10:07.373 --> 10:20.370
They went there They went to where the people were so they devoted themselves to fellowship shared meals and Opened homes every day hospitality

10:21.186 --> 10:23.068
It's the heart behind the welcome there.

10:25.691 --> 10:38.644
So for them, the church hospitality wasn't a department, wasn't a section of the business, it was a discipleship practice.

10:41.167 --> 10:47.794
So if you don't grab anything else, hospitality is a discipleship practice for the church even today.

10:49.762 --> 10:59.791
in Romans 12, it says, take a constant interest in the needs of God's beloved people and eagerly welcome people as guests into your home.

11:02.294 --> 11:07.619
True hospitality is an attitude, not an activity.

11:09.461 --> 11:19.410
The thing you need to know about this is you need to know that you have to open your arms first and your heart before you open the door.

11:21.474 --> 11:22.936
You can't make the adjustment later.

11:22.996 --> 11:24.238
You have to do it ahead of time.

11:26.481 --> 11:36.114
So when you have an open heart and your arms are ready to receive people, when you open a door, it is a spiritual statement.

11:39.839 --> 11:42.162
We have an open door policy where I work.

11:43.423 --> 11:44.164
I like it.

11:44.184 --> 11:48.330
We used to have one where I used to work back when I was in seminary.

11:49.211 --> 11:51.474
Well, they said,

11:51.682 --> 11:57.009
They had an open door policy because they were required to leave their office door open.

11:57.850 --> 12:04.960
It didn't mean what you would think an open door policy was where you can just go in and talk in any level to any level.

12:05.400 --> 12:06.702
That's not what that meant.

12:09.305 --> 12:10.167
But I didn't know that.

12:11.408 --> 12:13.091
I thought they met an open door policy.

12:13.131 --> 12:13.831
Was the doors open?

12:13.852 --> 12:14.392
You can go in.

12:15.434 --> 12:18.738
Back then I didn't have a lot of sense of boundaries, sense of

12:18.818 --> 12:22.022
where I couldn't, couldn't go, and I wondered into offices all over the place.

12:23.063 --> 12:24.404
They didn't like to add too much.

12:25.706 --> 12:26.687
But it's kind of funny.

12:26.707 --> 12:30.291
And later it was explained to me that doors are just open for show.

12:31.071 --> 12:34.615
We want to look like we're open, but we're really not.

12:35.496 --> 12:37.218
And I went, well, now you tell me.

12:38.720 --> 12:41.683
The one we haven't worked is truly an open door policy.

12:42.204 --> 12:48.050
Anybody can go anywhere at any time to talk to anybody, as long as they don't have something going on in there.

12:49.666 --> 12:56.515
But there's one person that secludes themselves in their office because they don't like to be invaded when they're doing their work.

12:57.076 --> 12:58.978
There's always one in the crowd, you know what I mean.

13:00.621 --> 13:08.010
And they don't like being available even if they're supposed to be because they want to get their stuff done in peace and quiet.

13:09.973 --> 13:19.666
But the door has a spiritual statement when it says, your need is probably more important than what I'm doing, but it's not important to me.

13:20.258 --> 13:21.780
That's a spiritual statement.

13:24.564 --> 13:36.078
So we make a statement with our door at home and our work and here at church, whether they are open or closed.

13:38.041 --> 13:41.125
Jesus said in John 10, I am the door.

13:42.727 --> 13:45.170
Anyone who wants to find peace comes through me.

13:45.858 --> 13:47.199
He's not a closed door.

13:47.379 --> 13:48.340
He's an open door.

13:48.541 --> 13:50.082
He welcomes all who will come.

13:50.142 --> 14:01.753
Every church door symbolizes that invitation from Jesus that all can come through, that they are welcome here, regardless of where that church is.

14:05.677 --> 14:15.666
An open door means that there's no invisible barriers of class, age, background, no favoritism, just

14:15.810 --> 14:43.250
Fellowship and welcome You are wanted here in Hebrews chapter 13 It says in the message be ready with a meal or a bed when it's needed Some have extended hospitality to angels without even knowing it Hospitality then is a ministry of anticipation not reaction or

14:43.906 --> 14:49.934
Anything else, it anticipates what you can do before it's needed and gets ready.

14:51.937 --> 14:53.739
Well, what are we anticipating here?

14:56.743 --> 14:58.285
What do we expect?

15:03.913 --> 15:07.858
Are our expectations in need of an update?

15:11.330 --> 15:24.967
I was at a church, I think it was Carol Illinois, and I think the church was since closed, but I went there and I spoke, and I looked on the back wall and said, you can expect a miracle here today.

15:26.949 --> 15:28.892
But it didn't look like anybody was expecting one.

15:31.435 --> 15:40.306
So every now and then, I asked myself this question, do I believe God can show up here today and create a miracle?

15:40.386 --> 15:41.989
or whatever's needed today.

15:43.691 --> 15:44.452
Do I believe that?

15:44.693 --> 15:45.935
If I don't believe that, why not?

15:46.015 --> 15:47.477
If I do, what am I doing about it?

15:49.260 --> 15:50.922
Same question you can ask yourself.

15:51.383 --> 16:08.530
But I think when the slogan, the jingle, the mantra of the United Methodist Church came out 30 years ago or so, open minds, open hearts, open doors, I thought they did pretty good with it, but they got it kind of wrong in one sense.

16:10.338 --> 16:14.742
Because they were trying to talk about everybody everywhere.

16:14.782 --> 16:18.366
We don't want to exclude anybody from anything, no matter who you are, no matter what you did.

16:18.406 --> 16:21.008
And the message was almost right.

16:23.811 --> 16:40.306
But it's first an open heart and then your door is open with open arms and you got to keep an open mind about what that means.

16:40.994 --> 16:57.237
Not everybody agrees with the slogan or the way it's presented, but if you understand the way I look at it and with the way I interpret it because that's how I interpret it as we are an open-hearted people.

16:57.898 --> 17:03.946
We have doors open to anybody and our minds say we can serve whoever God brings us.

17:05.208 --> 17:06.249
That's how I look at that.

17:06.590 --> 17:09.714
But if our hearts aren't involved

17:10.146 --> 17:15.131
and our arms aren't open, people will know your doors open but your arms are not.

17:16.312 --> 17:20.456
And so the arms part is missing in my mind from the slogan.

17:21.537 --> 17:24.239
You can have an open heart but keep your arms shut is what I'm saying.

17:26.522 --> 17:39.634
But can we as a church and as individuals implement how God really intended this to be with open heart, open arms aligned with Jesus Christ

17:40.002 --> 17:43.587
that when people come through an open door, they feel like they're wanted.

17:45.029 --> 17:48.313
Expected and cared for.

17:49.034 --> 17:53.700
No matter who it is, that's a good question to answer.

17:55.463 --> 18:00.410
But the reason I say this is because arms are so important.

18:01.291 --> 18:09.682
It's one of the greatest symbolistic, symbolic thing in the Bible that we can look at.

18:09.986 --> 18:18.256
When you see a story, you can see that either someone has returned away and resisting or they're open and receptive.

18:18.897 --> 18:29.050
And the reason the story of the prodigal son is so important isn't just because the father welcomes his son back, but it says he opens his arms.

18:30.592 --> 18:35.378
And his arms open because his heart has already been opened to him in his return.

18:38.946 --> 18:44.133
And he did this before the sun could utter a word of apology or confession.

18:46.696 --> 18:53.925
Welcoming people into the family of God is not contingent on their worthiness.

18:55.207 --> 18:57.350
It is driven by our compassion.

19:00.834 --> 19:07.122
Churches often stand at the window of the parable watching for the lost.

19:07.682 --> 19:13.108
welcoming them, but very few run down the driveway to find them.

19:15.410 --> 19:21.237
The ones who do become places of healing.

19:21.257 --> 19:28.444
You can tell the difference between a church going to the motions and a church in motion.

19:29.305 --> 19:29.906
Do you know what I mean?

19:31.407 --> 19:34.010
We were going Sunday, we did church.

19:34.391 --> 19:37.554
Now we're going to go back to life until next Sunday with the church.

19:37.794 --> 19:40.017
That's going through the motions.

19:40.398 --> 19:51.032
A church in motion is actually trying to seek to minister to care for beyond a Sunday morning, which is generally for those who are members and those who have been regularly attending.

19:51.072 --> 19:54.537
The rest of the week is for those who aren't there.

19:55.278 --> 19:56.960
And that's where the ministry is.

19:59.824 --> 20:03.128
What kind of church do we want to be and become?

20:03.669 --> 20:07.474
Because we have to keep becoming what God called us to be.

20:08.226 --> 20:10.749
And what kind of church has God called us to be?

20:10.789 --> 20:19.999
The kind of church that we are is dependent upon the culture that we establish here.

20:21.601 --> 20:25.545
And it's established, long before I ever got here, we had a culture established.

20:28.228 --> 20:37.458
And this church in my mind has created a culture of invitation, of welcoming, of loving, of receiving, of caring.

20:38.466 --> 20:42.772
of doing what it can to help in times of need in great ways.

20:46.458 --> 20:52.727
But brothers, fear, fatigue, or past disappointment can quietly build walls.

20:55.951 --> 21:01.399
But you know, walls that keep others out eventually trap us in.

21:02.881 --> 21:06.226
So we must always be willing to love readily.

21:06.786 --> 21:10.612
In Ephesians chapter 2 it says, Jesus is our peace.

21:11.173 --> 21:13.997
He broke down the wall of separation.

21:15.880 --> 21:20.267
And that was referring to it being broken down between the Jews and the Gentiles.

21:20.828 --> 21:27.258
And if Jesus can do that, we can tear down invisible ones between old members and new neighbors.

21:30.823 --> 21:31.905
It saddens me.

21:31.925 --> 21:35.250
And I've not seen it in a while because I'm here.

21:35.778 --> 22:04.338
but I've been in churches and it saddens me when there are people in the church that are odds with each other and they barely speak to each other and yet there they are saying I believe and I love people but I won't speak to them and they won't speak to me and we have this rift but we're still going to church together and we believe the same God we just don't believe the same thing about God that says love the brother or something like that right but what kind of message if someone comes

22:04.546 --> 22:12.295
and they see that, what does that give to people considering how to live the faith and learn from that kind of an example?

22:13.576 --> 22:14.437
This is okay.

22:15.919 --> 22:18.622
What part of the faith says that's okay?

22:21.025 --> 22:24.128
What part of love one another says that's okay?

22:26.131 --> 22:32.498
Where does forgiveness enter which is a primary part that makes Christianity different than any other thing?

22:32.738 --> 22:35.281
We live forgiven and we offer forgiveness.

22:37.665 --> 22:38.406
What would you like?

22:38.426 --> 22:44.914
Would you like to be a message of healing or a message of disparity in the faith?

22:46.356 --> 22:47.898
I think I know your answer.

22:50.982 --> 23:02.738
In Acts chapter 28, Paul talks about the blessing of an open church, of a gracious church, if you will, because Paul received all who came to him.

23:04.770 --> 23:13.284
opened armed churches, become centers of transformational expectation.

23:13.985 --> 23:16.869
That's a packed phrase.

23:16.889 --> 23:17.691
I'm going to say it again.

23:17.751 --> 23:18.572
I'm going to explain it.

23:19.033 --> 23:24.221
Open armed churches become centers of transformational expectation.

23:24.922 --> 23:29.810
In other words, every time we open a door, literally or relationally,

23:30.178 --> 23:34.324
We create a space where God does His best work, which is reconciliation.

23:34.644 --> 23:36.767
We expect God to do something.

23:37.428 --> 23:39.411
If someone's hurting, we expect God to heal.

23:39.511 --> 23:51.368
If they're suffering to comfort and we're part of the solution, we see we are part of God's transforming work to the people around us and we don't run from that.

23:52.730 --> 23:53.591
We run toward it.

23:55.473 --> 23:58.738
So we expect God to do something.

23:59.778 --> 24:01.458
Because that's what God does!

